 To draw a thick border around a specific 2x2 set of node cells in a TikZ diagram, you can use the `\draw` command with the `ultra thick` option, similar to how you've already used it for the rectangle at the beginning of your code.

For example, if you want to draw a thick border around the 2x2 group of cells that includes the nodes at (1,-1), (2,-1), (1,-2), and (2,-2), you would add:

```latex
\draw[ultra thick, red] (0.5,-0.5) rectangle ++(2,2);
```

The coordinates in the `\draw` command need to be adjusted to surround your nodes properly. In TikZ, nodes are placed at points, but the rectangle should enclose them, so you need to offset the starting coordinate and set an appropriate width and height.

Here's how you would modify your code to add a thick border around a 2x2 grid of cells (assuming your nodes are positioned with integer coordinates):

```latex
% Your existing code
\node[heade2] at (0, -5) {$\mathbf{t_y}$};
\node[headi3] at (0, -6) {$\mathbf{z}$};
\node[heade3] at (0, -7) {$\mathbf{t_z}$};
\draw[ultra thick] (0,0) rectangle ++(3,3);

% Multiplication table cells:
% Row 1, {tau: (tau, (i, t_i)) }
\node[zerocell] at (1, -1) {$0$};
\node[e1cell] at (2, -1) {$t_x$};
\node[i1cell] at (3, -1) {$-x$};
\node[e2cell] at (4, -1) {$t_y$};
\node[i2cell] at (5, -1) {$-y$};
\node[e3cell] at (6, -1) {$-t_z$};

% Draw thick border around a 2x2 grid (adjust coordinates as needed)
\draw[ultra thick, blue] (0.5,-1.5) rectangle ++(2,2);
```

This would draw a blue border around the 2×2 cells. You can adjust:

1. The starting coordinate `(0.5,-1.5)` to position the border correctly
2. The size `++(2,2)` to make it larger or smaller
3. The color (blue, red, green, etc.)
4. Other style options like `dashed`, `dotted`, or `line width=2pt` for more customization

If you need to highlight specific non-adjacent cells, you might need multiple rectangle commands or consider using a different approach like node backgrounds.

