 The "option clash" error occurs when the `xcolor` package is loaded multiple times with different options. This typically happens because:

1. You're explicitly loading `xcolor` with options after it has already been loaded by another package (like TikZ)
2. Or another package loaded `xcolor` with different options than what you're trying to use

Here are a few ways to fix this:

## Solution 1: Load xcolor BEFORE TikZ

```latex
\usepackage[dvipsnames,svgnames,x11names]{xcolor}
\usepackage{tikz}
```

## Solution 2: Pass the options to the document class

```latex
\documentclass[dvipsnames,svgnames,x11names]{article}
% ... other packages
\usepackage{tikz}
```

## Solution 3: Use \PassOptionsToPackage

This is the most reliable solution when you're not sure about the loading order:

```latex
\PassOptionsToPackage{dvipsnames,svgnames,x11names}{xcolor}
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
```

## Solution 4: Load TikZ with the color options

TikZ loads xcolor internally, so you can pass the options to TikZ:

```latex
\usepackage[dvipsnames,svgnames,x11names]{tikz}
```

Even without the extra color packages, you can still use the basic colors and define your own custom colors with RGB values:

```latex
% Define custom colors
\definecolor{darkblue}{RGB}{0,0,139}
\definecolor{lightgreen}{RGB}{144,238,144}
\definecolor{salmon}{RGB}{250,128,114}

% Use them in your diagram
\node[draw, ultra thick, darkblue, fit=(n11) (n12) (n21) (n22), inner sep=2pt] {};
```

Try one of these approaches and the option clash error should be resolved.

