 To define colors from the xcolor package, you can use the `\definecolor` command. Here's how to do it:

## Basic Color Definition

```latex
\definecolor{colorname}{color-model}{color-specification}
```

Where:
- `colorname` is the name you want to give your color
- `color-model` is the model you're using (like RGB, rgb, HTML, etc.)
- `color-specification` is the actual color values

## Common Color Models

1. **RGB (0-255 scale)**:
```latex
\definecolor{myblue}{RGB}{100, 150, 200}
```

2. **rgb (0-1 scale)**:
```latex
\definecolor{myred}{rgb}{0.8, 0.2, 0.3}
```

3. **HTML/Hex code**:
```latex
\definecolor{mypurple}{HTML}{8A2BE2}
```

4. **cmyk (for printing)**:
```latex
\definecolor{mycyan}{cmyk}{1, 0, 0, 0}
```

5. **Gray scale**:
```latex
\definecolor{lightgray}{gray}{0.85}
```

## Using Color Mixtures

You can also define colors as mixtures of existing colors:

```latex
\colorlet{mylightblue}{blue!40!white}  % 40% blue mixed with 60% white
\colorlet{darkgreen}{green!50!black}   % 50% green mixed with 50% black
```

## Practical Example

```latex
% Load xcolor with options (remember to handle option clash as discussed before)
\PassOptionsToPackage{dvipsnames,svgnames,x11names}{xcolor}
\usepackage{tikz}

% Define some custom colors
\definecolor{navy}{RGB}{0, 0, 128}
\definecolor{coral}{RGB}{255, 127, 80}
\definecolor{forestgreen}{RGB}{34, 139, 34}
\definecolor{goldenrod}{RGB}{218, 165, 32}

% Create color variations
\colorlet{lightnav}{navy!70!white}
\colorlet{darkcoral}{coral!70!black}

% Use these colors in TikZ
\begin{tikzpicture}
  \node[draw=navy, fill=lightnav, thick] at (0,0) {Navy text};
  \node[draw=coral, fill=darkcoral, thick] at (2,0) {Coral text};
  \draw[forestgreen, ultra thick] (0,1) -- (2,1);
  \draw[goldenrod, ultra thick] (0,2) -- (2,2);
\end{tikzpicture}
```

After defining colors this way, you can use them anywhere in your document where colors are accepted, including in your TikZ borders:

```latex
\node[draw, ultra thick, navy, fit=(n11) (n12) (n21) (n22), inner sep=2pt] {};
```

Remember to handle the xcolor package loading properly to avoid option clashes, using one of the methods I mentioned in the previous response.

