 To fix the overlapping lines and inconsistent spacing in your TikZ diagram, I recommend these approaches:

1. **Use layered drawing with different z-index values**:
   ```latex
   \pgfdeclarelayer{background}
   \pgfdeclarelayer{foreground}
   \pgfsetlayers{background,main,foreground}
   ```

2. **Create a consistent spacing strategy**:
   ```latex
   % Define a consistent inner sep value
   \newcommand{\myinnersep}{2pt}
   ```

3. **Apply rounded corners** to make overlapping less noticeable:
   ```latex
   \node[draw, ultra thick, black, rounded corners=2pt, fit=(n00) (n70) (n07) (n77), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
   ```

4. **Use different line styles** for adjacent boxes:
   ```latex
   % Mix of solid and dashed lines
   \node[draw, ultra thick, dred, solid, fit=(n02) (n03) (n12) (n13), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
   \node[draw, ultra thick, dyellow, dashed, fit=(n04) (n05) (n14) (n15), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
   ```

5. **Create a rectangle drawing command** with consistent parameters:
   ```latex
   \newcommand{\drawblock}[5]{
     \node[draw, ultra thick, #1, fit=(#2) (#3) (#4) (#5), inner sep=\myinnersep, rounded corners=1pt] {};
   }

   % Then use:
   \drawblock{dred}{n02}{n03}{n12}{n13}
   \drawblock{dyellow}{n04}{n05}{n14}{n15}
   ```

6. **Add a small offset to each rectangle** to prevent exact overlapping:
   ```latex
   \node[draw, ultra thick, black, fit=(n00) (n70) (n07) (n77), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
   \node[draw, ultra thick, dred, fit=($(n02)+(-0.1,0.1)$) ($(n03)+(0.1,0.1)$) ($(n12)+(-0.1,-0.1)$) ($(n13)+(0.1,-0.1)$), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
   ```

A comprehensive solution would combine several of these approaches:

```latex
% Setup layers
\pgfdeclarelayer{background}
\pgfdeclarelayer{middle}
\pgfdeclarelayer{foreground}
\pgfsetlayers{background,middle,main,foreground}

% Define consistent spacing
\newcommand{\myinnersep}{1.5pt}

% Draw the outermost rectangle in the background
\begin{pgfonlayer}{background}
  \node[draw, ultra thick, black, rounded corners=1pt, fit=(n00) (n70) (n07) (n77), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
\end{pgfonlayer}

% Draw the medium-sized rectangles in the middle layer
\begin{pgfonlayer}{middle}
  \node[draw, ultra thick, dred, rounded corners=1pt, fit=(n02) (n03) (n12) (n13), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
  \node[draw, ultra thick, dyellow, rounded corners=1pt, fit=(n04) (n05) (n14) (n15), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
  % ... other medium rectangles
\end{pgfonlayer}

% Draw the smallest rectangles in the foreground
\begin{pgfonlayer}{foreground}
  \node[draw, ultra thick, dorange, rounded corners=1pt, fit=(n22) (n23) (n32) (n33), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
  \node[draw, ultra thick, dgreen, rounded corners=1pt, fit=(n44) (n45) (n54) (n55), inner sep=\myinnersep] {};
  % ... other small rectangles
\end{pgfonlayer}
```

This layered approach will give you much more control over which lines appear on top of others, creating a cleaner visual hierarchy.

